Summary

Chrome is unshipping its implementation of the HTML Sanitizer API while a significant specification update is being worked on (see https://chromestatus.com/feature/5115076981293056).

This PR updates the BCD to account for this.

I've not listed the features as deprecated, as in this case the API is not being removed, rather it is being updated significantly.

Test results and supporting details

items.content_html:
Summary

The new script does the following:

  • Read a specific chromestatus page to get information about current, nightly, and beta versions of Chrome for Desktop and Chrome for Android
  • "Guess" (and check) the URL for the release notes of the last current Chrome for desktop / Chrome for android
  • update the local BCD files chrome.json, chrome_android.json, and webview_android.json`.

Once landed, the goal is to run it once and manually create a PR for the change. After this, the plan is to add an action to do that automatically and create a PR with the change to the browser files.

Notes:

  • script should be run in the directory containing "chrome.json" / "chrome_android.json".
  • I found a chromestatus bug that returns an invalid JSON file. This script works around the problem. This is well commented on in the bug. We will follow up with Google, but not blocking
  • There is no definitive way to find the URL of the release notes, so I guess it (in a function where I test if it works, checking if the page HTTP status is 200).
  • Assumed that:
    • "stable" in chromestatus is "release" in BCD
    • "beta" is "beta"
    • ""canary" (not "dev") is "nightly"
      These are constants in the code, so it is trivial to change this mapping
  • Errors and warnings are logged on the console; this will be done while working on using it as a GitHub action.
  • Chromestatus doesn't have the whole history of release: if there is a gap, the script will log a warning.

Test results and supporting details

Manually tested.

Related issues

Part of the automation project.
items.title: Add script to update {chrome|chrome_android|webview_android}.json with new browser versions

items.content_html:
FF119 allows SubtleCrypto.deriveKey() to support HKDF as a derivedKeyAlgorithm in https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1851928

I have not fully tested all the support options, as even the engineer I asked wasn't sure what tests map to what features in http://wpt.live/WebCryptoAPI/derive_bits_keys/. However it was stated that this is supported in Chrome. What I have done is mapped the version here to the same as the parent for other browsers. Then checked where possible - e.g. I can find that in deno this is supported in that first version https://deno.land/api@v1.37.1?s=SubtleCrypto#method_deriveKey_13.

EDIT
There are at least 4 possible algorithms to derivedKeyAlgorithm: HMAC, PBKDF2, HKDF, and AES. There are also a bunch of values that can be passed as the main algorithm, and also hash algorithms that can be used by some of these. So it is a big complicated mess, little of which is capture currently.

What I have done is added derivedKeyAlgorithm subfeatures for: HMAC, PBKDF2, HKDF, and AES.

  • I know nodejs supports AES and HMAC from first version 20ish
  • I know Deno supports all options from 1.15
  • I know FF supports HKDF from 119, and probably HMAC and AES since first version.
    There is a bug for supporting PBKDF2 which I have linked.
  • Chrome seems to have supported all algorithms from first version.
  • Safari has no information. I have put false because if it is wrong people are more likely to complain and fix it.
  • I think we should expand this approach for all the algorithms on all the methods in this API. However I don't have time to do this, and we'd want to have test code to do it properly in the collector @queengooborg

Hope this is good enough, even though we know it might not be "100%"

Related docs work can be tracked in mdn/content#29411.
items.title: FF119 SubtleCrypto.deriveKey() supports HKDF as a derivedKeyAlgorith option

items.content_html:
Summary

Resolves #20795

Some but not all notes entries mention bug tickets that especially resolve a missing functionality for feature completeness against the standard, that for I've included this one within the new impl_url entry, but not the previous, "original" bug ticket (with which the ticket has been partially implemented) for two reasons:

  • easier implementation: I would have needed to research the original ticket with the partial implementation
  • relevance: From my understanding the impl_url entries relevance is mainly about "feature completeness", so it would be more relevant to have an insight into the remaining work, than an already resolved ticket.

Test results and supporting details

items.content_html:
Summary

Add an api/ entry for Secure Payment Confirmation. It consists of three main sub-features:

  1. PaymentCredentialInstrument, a dictionary (minor)
  2. payment-extension, a WebAuthn extension that the SPC spec defines
  3. secure-payment-confirmation, a Payment Request payment method that the SPC spec defines

Test results and supporting details

Data was written using the author's knowledge of when SPC released on Chrome, and which other browsers inherit from Chrome. Some of this still needs to be manually verified, such as the status on Opera and Samsung Internet Browser.
items.title: Add BCD data for Secure Payment Confirmation
